    "Finally, the cultural selection framework assumes that some variants spread more rapidly than others, making evolution a process that is not neutral, but subject to biases (e.g.",
    "systematic cognitive and transmission patterns deviating from rationality) or selection pressures (e.g.",
    "environmental factors that affect fitness of variants) (Boyd & Richerson, 1985; Hagen & Hammerstein, 2006; Henrich & McElreath, 2007; Vale et al., 2017).",
    "While modelling frameworks make distinctive assumptions about the nature of cultural processes, these frameworks can each be instantiated at either of two common scales.",
    "Regarding the scale used to model cultural evolution, researchers in the field have distinguished between two general classes (Van Dyke Parunak et al., 1998; Kandler et al., 2012)."
